Assign product <strong>custom option title</strong> to a variable that will be used in custom math formula.
<br/><br/>
<strong>Option types supported:</strong> <em>Checkbox, Drop-down, Text Field, Radio Button</em>
<br/><br/>
<strong>Mapping format:</strong> <em>Custom Option Title=&gt;your_variable_name;</em>
<br/><br/>
<strong>Example:</strong><code>
<br/>Banner Width=&gt;bw;
<br/>Canvas Height=&gt;ch;
<br/>Material Type=&gt;mt;
<br/>Finishing Options=&gt;fo;
<br/>Glass Color=&gt;glass;
<br/>Frame Type=&gt;frame_type;
<br/>...</code><br/>
<br/><small>NOTE: We suggest one mapping per line for readability. Terminate each line with semi-colon. Use only lower-case letters for variable names and _underscores if you need to break up multiple words. <strong>Formula logic will fail if the custom option title is not an EXACT match to the product configuration, be sure to copy/paste your custom option title from product configuration page when mapping to a variable here.</strong></small>
<br/><br/>

Define variables that are not bound to any attribute or custom option but are still needed in your calculation. Variables can be the result of other {variables} from <strong>1.1</strong>, <strong>1.2</strong>, and <strong>1.3</strong>.
<br/><br/><strong>Mapping format:</strong> <em>variable_name=&gt;expression;</em> <strong>OR</strong> <em>variable_name=&gt;value;</em>
<br/><br/>
<strong>Example:</strong><code>
<br/>a=&gt;{b} * {c};
<br/>d=&gt;{a} * 125;
<br/>ba=&gt;{bw}*{bh};
<br/>banner_discount=&gt;({ba} > 20) && ({ba} <= 50) ? 10 : 0;
<br/>discount_one=&gt;({qty} &gt; 10) &amp;&amp; ({qty} &lt;= 20)? 1 : 0;
<br/>discount_two=&gt;({qty} &gt; 20) &amp;&amp; ({qty} &lt;= 50)? 1 : 0;
<br/>discount_three=&gt;({qty} &gt; 50) &amp;&amp; ({qty} &lt;= 100)? 1 : 0;
<br/>discount_four=&gt;({qty} &gt; 100)? 1 : 0;
<br/>...</code><br/>
<br/><strong>Supported operators:</strong> <em>Calculation, Comparison and Conditional (<a href="#cmp_math-head">Reference</a>)</em>
<br/><strong>Supported functions:</strong> <em>abs, ceil, floor, round</em>
<br/><strong>Reserved variable names:</strong> <em>Avoid using reserved variable names and reserved underscore _suffixes (<a href="#cmp_math-head">Reference</a>)</em><br>
<br/><small>NOTE: We suggest one mapping per line for readability. Terminate each line with semi-colon. Use only lower-case letters for variable names and _underscores if you need to break up multiple words.</small>
<br/><br/>

Set special values for variables defined in 1.2 and 1.3.
<br/><br/>
<strong>Mapping format:</strong> <em>{your_variable_name}=&gt;value;</em>
<br/><br/>
<strong>Example:</strong><code>
<br/>{width_default}=&gt;1;
<br/>{height_default}=&gt;1;
<br/>{width}_{one}=&gt;1;
<br/>{width}_{two}=&gt;2;
<br/>{glass}=&gt;1;
<br/>{20 feet}=&gt;240;
<br/>{20 inches}=&gt;20;
<br/>{retailer}=>2;
<br/>{guest}=>3;
<br/>{customergroup}_{retailer}=>2;
<br/>{customergroup}_{guest}=>3;
<br/>...</code>
<br/><br/>
<small>Note: The values set in 1.4 get passed to price logic only. They <b>are not visible</b> on the product page as the option price. They are used in the final price calculation. Also, to use <strong>Customer Group</strong> variables in your formula, make sure you have <a href="#row_cmp_labels_cmpQty" title="Jump to 1.15">1.15</a> set to <strong>Yes.</strong></small>
<br/><br/>

Used for overriding per-product custom math logic and variables. This is where you map the attribute codes for each input area shown on the product config page.
<br/><br/>
<strong>Attribute types supported:</strong> <em>Text Area (Global Scope), Text Field (Global Scope)</em>
<br/><br/>
<strong>Mapping format:</strong> <em>reserved_cmp_feature_name=&gt;your_attribute_code</em>
<br/><br/>
<small>We suggest to copy the example values below so you don't have to manually create the attributes in your store. However, some multi-lang store owners prefer to create the attributes in their own language so it is possible to create them on your own and manually map each attribute to the correct cmp_override_feature, the choice is yours.
<br/><br/>
See section 2.9 below for instructions on how to auto-create the required attributes.</small>
<br/><br/>
<strong>Example:</strong>
<br/><code>options=&gt;mico_cmp_options;
<br/>nonoptions=&gt;mico_cmp_non_options;
<br/>values=&gt;mico_cmp_values;
<br/>init=&gt;mico_cmp_init;
<br/>min=&gt;mico_cmp_min;
<br/>max=&gt;mico_cmp_max;
<br/>validations=&gt;mico_cmp_validations;
<br/>custompriceremove=&gt;mico_cmp_custompriceremove;
<br/>unit=&gt;mico_cmp_unit;
<br/>unit_options=&gt;mico_cmp_unit_options;
<br/>price=&gt;mico_cmp_price;
<br/>upcharge=&gt;mico_cmp_upcharge;
<br/>qty=&gt;mico_cmp_qty;
<br/>weight=&gt;mico_cmp_weight;
<br/>relations=&gt;mico_cmp_relations;
<br/>csvrow=&gt;mico_cmp_csvrow;
<br/>csvcol=&gt;mico_cmp_csvcol;

</code>
<br/><br/>
<strong>Override Config Mapping Explained:</strong>
<br/><strong>price:</strong> <i>price logic</i>
<br/><strong>unit:</strong> <i>unit conversion</i>
<br/><strong>unit_options:</strong> <i>variables that use unit conversion</i>
<br/><strong>qty:</strong> <i>subtract qty logic</i>
<br/><strong>weight:</strong> <i>weight logic</i>
<br/><strong>upcharge:</strong> <i>upcharge logic</i>
<br/><strong>options:</strong> <i>option labels</i>
<br/><strong>nonoptions:</strong> <i>non-option variable</i>
<br/><strong>init:</strong> <i>variable init values</i>
<br/><strong>values:</strong> <i>special option values</i>
<br/><strong>min:</strong> <i>min input validation</i>
<br/><strong>max:</strong> <i>max input validation</i>
<br/><strong>validations:</strong> <i>custom validation and alert</i>
<br/><strong>custompriceremove:</strong> <i>remove custom price</i>
<br/><br/>
